{"cursor":"95362","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n\n'Capitalism' is an economic system based on the private ownership of capital\ngoods and the means of production, with the creation of goods and services for\nprofit. Chris Jenks. Core Sociological Dichotomies. London, England, UK;\nThousand Oaks, California, USA; New Delhi, India: SAGE. p.\n383. [http://oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/capitalism\nCapitalism] Oxford Dictionaries. Retrieved 4 January 2013. Elements\ncentral to capitalism include capital accumulation, competitive markets, and a\nprice system. Heilbroner, Robert L.\n[http://www.dictionaryofeconomics.com/article?id=pde2008_C000053 \"capitalism.\"]\nThe New Palgrave Dictionary of Economics. Second Edition. Steven N. Durlauf and\nLawrence E. Blume (Eds.). Palgrave Macmillan, 2008. \n\nThere are multiple variants of capitalism, including laissez-faire, welfare\ncapitalism and state capitalism. Capitalism is considered to have been applied\nin a variety of historical cases, varying in time, geography, politics, and\nculture. There is general agreement that capitalism became\ndominant in the Western world following the demise of feudalism.\n\nEconomists (including political economists) and historians have taken different\nperspectives on the analysis of capitalism. Economists usually emphasize the\ndegree to which government does not have control over markets (laissez-faire),\nas well as the importance of property rights. Most\npolitical economists emphasize private property as well, in addition to power\nrelations, wage labor, class, and the uniqueness of capitalism as a historical\nformation. The extent to which different markets are free,\nas well as the rules defining private property, is a matter of politics and\npolicy. Many states have what are termed mixed economies, referring to the\nvarying degree of planned and market-driven elements in an economic system. Stilwell, Frank. âPolitical Economy: the Contest of Economic\nIdeas.â First Edition. Oxford University Press. Melbourne, Australia.\n2002.\n\nIn the 20th century defenders of the capitalist system often replaced the terms\ncapitalism with phrases such as free enterprise and private enterprise and\ncapitalist with [[investor]] in reaction to the negative connotations sometimes\nassociated with capitalism.\n\nThe term capitalism, in its modern sense, comes from the writings of Karl\nMarx. \n","linknr":1664,"url":"Capitalism","recorded":1362480794,"links":162,"instances":["financial_aid","economics","polity","economics","discipline","economics","economics","writer","finance","geographer","accounting","sociology","business","economics","economist","economics","economics"],"pdf":["http://www.hbs.edu/research/pdf/07-037.pdf","http://www.hbs.edu/research/pdf/07-037.pdf","http://www.economyandsociety.com/events/Ethic&SpiritCapsm_Conf_Agenda2.pdf","http://www.economyandsociety.com/events/Ethic&SpiritCapsm_Conf_Agenda2.pdf"],"categories":["Capitalism|","Capitalist systems|","Economic ideologies","Economic liberalism","Economic systems","Economies","Ideologies","Individualism","Political economy","Social philosophy"],"headings":["Economic elements","Types of capitalism","Etymology and early usage","History","Perspectives","Neoclassical economic theory","Democracy, the state, and legal frameworks","Advocacy for capitalism","Criticisms","See also","Notes","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/85/Economic_template.svg/50px-Economic_template.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fd/Portal-puzzle.svg/16px-Portal-puzzle.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fd/Portal-puzzle.svg/16px-Portal-puzzle.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fd/Portal-puzzle.svg/16px-Portal-puzzle.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fd/Portal-puzzle.svg/16px-Portal-puzzle.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Emblem-m